definition.value: An organophosphate oxoanion that is the tetraanion obtained by the deprotonation of all the phosphate OH groups of eritoran.
An EC 3.4.14.* (dipeptidyl- and tripeptidyl-peptidases) inhibitor that specifically inhibits dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (EC 3.4.14.5).
A C4-dicarboxylate which is a dianion obtained by the deprotonation of the two carboxy OH groups of aurothiomalic acid.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as (2E)-3-phenylprop-2-enoyl (cinnamoyl).
A phenolate anion which is a dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the phenolic OH groups of eosin b diphenol.
A C-nitro compound which consists of a fluorescein skeleton substituted by bromo groups at positions 4 and 5 and nitro groups at positions 2 and 7.

A branched amino pentasaccharide comprising a linear sequence of alpha-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, beta-D-galactosamine and beta-D-glucosamine residues linked (1->3), (1->4) and (1->4), with an N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminic acid residue linked (2->6) to the N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue.
A carboxylic acid anion obtained by global deprotonation of the carboxy groups of poly(4-vinylbenzoic acid).

A synthetic tripeptide consisting of N-(tert-butylcarbamoyl)-3-methyl-L-valyl, a cyclopropyl-fused prolyl and 3-amino-4-cyclobutyl-2-oxobutanamide residues joined in sequence. Used for treatment of chronic hepatitis C virus genotype 1 infection.

An amino pentasaccharide consisting of N-acetylneuraminic acid, beta-D-galactopyranose, 2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucopyranose and 2-acetamido-2-deoxygalactoyranose residues joined in sequence by (2->3), (1->4), and (1->6) glycosidic bonds in which the hydroxy group at position 3 of the 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-D-galactopyranose moiety bearing the anomeric hydroxy group has been converted to the corresponding beta-D-galactopyranoside.
A UDP-N-acetyl-D-mannosamine(2-) in which the anomeric centre of the pyranose fragment has alpha-configuration.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at C-12 and C-14 (the former with Z-stereochemistry) and carries a hydroxy group at position C-8.
A bicyclic sesquiterpene that is 2,4,5,6,7,7a-hexahydro-1H-indene substituted at positions 3 and 7 by methyl groups and at position 4 by a 3,3-dimethylallyl group (the 4S,7R,7aR-stereoisomer).
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of valerenic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A vinyl polymer macromolecule composed of repeating 4-ethylbenzoic acid units.
An organosulfonate oxoanion which is also a monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo and carboxy groups of tartrazine acid.
A pyrazoles which is pyrazole-3-carboxylic acid substituted by an oxo group at position 5, a 4-sulfophenyl group at position 1 and (4-sulfophenyl)diazenyl group at position 4.

An organochlorine compound that is urea in which the two hydrogens on one of the amino groups are replaced by nitroso and 2-chloroethyl groups and one hydrogen from the other amino group is replaced by a 4-methylcyclohexyl group.
An organosulfonate oxoanion which is the trianion obtained by the deprotonation of the sulfo groups of tetrasulfocyanine acid.
A arenesulfonic acid in which two sulfonated indole moieties are linked via a 4-methylhepta-1,3,5-triene-1,7-diyl chain.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the carboxy groups of poly(acrylic acid).
A steroid phosphate oxoanion which is the dianion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of cortisol phosphate.
A steroid phosphate that is the 21-O-phospho derivative of cortisol.
An organic sodium salt that is the trisodium salt of guanosine 5'-(beta,gamma-methylene)triphosphate.
An enone in which a 4-hydroxyphenyl group is attached to the beta-carbon atom of but-3-en-2-one.
A steroid phosphate that is the 21-O-phospho derivative of dexamethasone.
A steroid phosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of dexamethasone phosphate.

A sterol ester obtained by formal condensation of the 3-hydroxy group of abiraterone with the carboxy group of acetic acid. A prodrug that is converted in vivo into abiraterone. Used for treatment of metastatic castrate-resistant prostate cancer.

An EC 1.14.99.* (miscellaneous oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, with incorporation or reduction of molecular oxygen) inhibitor that interferes with the action of cytochrome P450 17-alpha-hydroxylase/C17,20-lyase (EC 1.14.99.9).
An N-alkylpyrrolidine that consists of N-methylpyrrolidinone bearing a pyridin-3-yl substituent at position C-5 (the 5S-enantiomer). It is an alkaloid commonly found in Nicotiana tabacum.

A 3beta-sterol that is androsta-5,16-dien-3beta-ol substituted at position 17 by a 3-pyridyl group. Administered as the O-acetate, it is used for treatment of metastatic castrate-resistant prostate cancer.
A steroid phosphate which is the 17-O-phospho derivative of estramustine.
A steroid phosphate oxoanion which is the dianion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of estramustine phosphate.
An amino sugar that consists of 6-deoxy-alpha-D-mannose having the hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 4 replaced by acetamido groups.

A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of anhydrous regorafenib. Used for for the treatment of metastatic colorectal cancer in patients who have previously received chemotherapy, anti-EGFR or anti-VEGF therapy.

A pyridinecarboxamide obtained by condensation of 4-[4-({[4-chloro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]carbamoyl}amino)-3-fluorophenoxy]pyridine-2-carboxylic acid with methylamine. Used for for the treatment of metastatic colorectal cancer in patients who have previously received chemotherapy, anti-EGFR or anti-VEGF therapy.
An organotellurium compound that is ditellane in which the two hydrogens are replaced by methyl groups.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of pentalenic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 1-deoxypentalenic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->3)-alpha-D-diNAcBac-tritrans,heptacis-undecaprenyl diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.

An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-N,N'-diacetyl-alpha-D-bacillosaminyl-tritrans,heptacis-undecaprenyl diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.

An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of [alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->4)]4-alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->3)-alpha-D-diNAcBac-tritrans,heptacis-undecaprenyl diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.

An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of [alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->4)]2-[beta-D-Glc-(1->3)]-[alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->4)]2-alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->3)-alpha-D-diNAcBac-tritrans,heptacis-undecaprenyl diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricyclic sesquiterpene that is 2,4,4a,5,6,7,7a,7b-octahydro-1H-cyclobuta[e]indene bearing four methyl substituents at positions 3, 6, 6 and 7b.

A ketone that is 4-phenylbutan-2-one in which the phenyl ring is substituted at position 4 by a hydroxy group. It is found in a variety of fruits including raspberries, blackberries and cranberries, and is used in perfumery and cosmetics.
A methyl ketone that is 4-phenylbutan-2-one in which the phenyl ring is substituted at positions 3 and 4 by methoxy and hydroxy groups respectively. The major pungent component in ginger.
A sesquiterpenoid that is bisabolane having double bonds at positions 2 and 9 as well as a hydroxy substituent at position 7.
An organic cation obtained by the protonation of the amino group of FR901469.

A 40-membered macrocyclic cyclodepsipeptide that consists of a 3-hydroxypalmitoyl moiety linked to a peptide sequence of 12 amino acids and cyclised head-to-tail. It is isolated from an unidentified Fungus and exhibits antifungal activity.
A sialotetraosylceramide consisting of the disialoganglioside GD1b with a lactone ring formed between the two NeuNac residues (between C-1 of the most terminal one and C-9 of the more proximal one).
